    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Mya lutraria</i><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1055",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Very large and oblong with relatively thin shell valves. Shell gapes widely at both ends when alive. Hinge displaced towards anterior end and has a very prominent spoon-shaped ligamental pit. Exterior surface white, often stained a dirty yellow. The live animal has a very large, fleshy foot that protrudes from the shell and massive siphons that are fused along their length and can be extended to 2-3 times the length of the shells.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1056",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 137 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1057",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in Europe and Mediterranean and also Namibia and South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> &nbsp;Namibia to about Port Alfred</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1058",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Burrows deeply in fine sediments from low water to about 100 m depth. Seldom seen alive, as it lives so deeply buries below the sand surface, but shells commonly washed up after storms.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1059",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves feeds by pumping water in via an inhalant siphon, filtering out fine particles though the enlarged gills and then ejecting the filtered water through an exhalent siphon.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1060",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves is a broadcast spawner. Details of reproductive cycle of this species in South Africa have not been investigated.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1061",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Adults unlikely to be confused with other regional species due to their very large size and unusual elongated and open-ended shell. Other species of<i> Lutraria </i>occur on the east coast, but do not extend into the Western Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1062",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 152).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 179).<br><br>Signorelli, JH (2021). The Family Mactridae Lamarck, 1809 (Bivalvia: Cardiida) in South African Waters. <i>Malacologia</i>, 63(2), 195-223.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1063",
